BODY: Ok  just read the backlog. That doesn't sound like a good idea.1) Leaks metadata of who is in a group.2) More things to keep in Redis3) More bandwidth usage because those message will be sent out every time you connect to the socket and will eventually pile up over time.For the record:13:20 < _corbett> no. so b) say I get a message from someone in a group that I have left (due to asynchronicity). does the UI display?13:21 <@lilia> _corbett: oh i see13:21 <@lilia> i think we ignore any group messages before the create13:21 < jakeok> intuitively  i'd say don't display it13:21 < _corbett> or a) say I get a message for a group prior to getting the group create message (due to asychronicity) do I wait for the latter? display immediately?13:21 <@lilia> and send a leave-group to any messages received after the leave13:21 < _corbett> wellll…. it could happen I get messages out of order13:21 <@lilia> but odnt display them13:21 < _corbett> so the person sent the message thinking I was still a member of the group13:22 <@lilia> _corbett: you need to send them a leave group message until they stop13:22 < jakeok> yeah i feel like the right way to do it technically is to keep the messages stored  and if you get an initial group context  you can display those messages in the conversation that you received prior to the create13:22 <@rhodey> jakeok: ok  thanks for the heads up13:22 < _corbett> yes… but that breaks our asychronicity too I think. we don’t wait typically13:22 < _corbett> or try to impose order re a)13:22 < _corbett> so I’m both wondering how android handles it  and if we want to handle it that way long term13:23 <@lilia> i would not store rando group messages in the hope that the create is coming13:23 < _corbett> for now I want to handle it exactly as android. I can just read the code.13:23 < _corbett> hmmmm…. but what if there is just one create sent?13:23 < _corbett> if you somehow missed it you will *never* get a message of the group13:23 < _corbett> also breaks things I think.13:24 <@lilia> the server should resend the group create until you 200OK it13:24 < jakeok> unfortunately group messages are one of the few stateful things here13:24 < _corbett> this is what I was unclear about and am asking about13:24 <@lilia> thats how websocket resources work13:24 < jlund> Still getting a lot of reports of unreliable message delivery  just to add more fodder to the current conversation.13:24 <@lilia> if you dont ack the message with 200 OK response it will retry13:24 < _corbett> still like the creator fires off the create and then 10 messages and then some people respond. but for some reason on my phone it didn’t get the create13:25 < _corbett> finally I 200OK it but in the meantime everyone in the group planned dinner thinking I was in the gorup13:25 <@lilia> lol13:25 < _corbett> I drop all those messages?13:26 < jlund> jakeok: Do you know if the plan is to switch to using WebSockets for message delivery/retrieval on the Android side with GCM serving as a means of waking up the socket (similar to iOS)?13:26 <@lilia> just dont 200OK the group messages  the server should have your back13:26 < jakeok> jlund: that's my impression and hope13:26 < jakeok> GCM is bad news bears13:26 < jakeok> so we should just use it for signaling to connect

BODY: The word "created" is problematic. If the image or video was not captured by the camera  then we don't know when it was created. AUTHOR: weaverryan
BODY: Actually  nevermind. I think that using `require` isn't the best idea for Symfony  because we tell people to use `2.6.*`-style requirements  instead of `~2.6`  I guess to be a bit more conservative. Using `require` would - I believe - give us the tilde version. I did sort of re-word this section though. I think we should actually tell people to use `composer update` to upgrade their libraries. I think if they actually want a full new version of some non-Symfony library that's beyond what they originally put in their composer.json file  then they're on their own to do that (and this would be a common thing to do with Composer). Also  assuming more and more people use `composer require` to initially add a library  people will have constraints like `~1.2` more and more commonly  which means "update" will allow them patch and minor versions (and it make sense for them to knowingly opt-in if they want to change the major version).

BODY: I was debating whether or not to do that. I decided not to because the Skeleton is responsible for DOF name management (because each DOF in the skeleton must have a unique name)  so accessing DOFs by name should be done through the skeleton.Having the joints also keep track of DOF names seems redundant. And if we gave the joint class a function that uses the skeleton to look up DOFs it could be strange/confusing if someone asks a joint for a DOF that belongs to another joint.In my mind  the thing that makes the most sense is asking the Skeleton for access to a DOF if you want to access by name  and you should only go through the Joint to access a DOF if you want to access it by its index within that Joint.Let me know if that doesn't make sense.

AUTHOR: kenzierocks
BODY: You can declare an `ImmutableList` holding the arguments that take location:```private static final ImmutableList<String> LOCATION_DEPENDENT_ARGS = ImmutableList.of("x"  "y"  "z"  "dx"  "dy"  "dz"  "rm"  "r");```And use [`Collections.disjoint(Collection a  Collection b)`](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Collections.html#disjoint%28java.util.Collection %20java.util.Collection%29) to determine the collision:```boolean requiresLocation = !Collections.disjoin(this.arguments  LOCATION_DEPENDENT_ARGS) || this.type.equals(SelectorTypes.NEAREST_PLAYER);```Which is much easier to read + maintain.

AUTHOR: pkolaczk
BODY: Yes  but I wonder if it is worth the effort. It will require one additional array for storing hashes (of size capacity * 2)  plus extra calls to save hashes (probably negligible) plus an extra compare + conditional jump in find() before comparing the key; which depending on the circumstances can be anything between ~2-4 CPU cycles (L1 cache hit   branch predicted) through ~7-15 CPU cycles (cache hit  branch mispredicted) to 1000+ CPU cycles worstcase (L2 cache miss when referencing the hashcodes array; quite improbable though considering our size of the queue). Most keys are found *in the first iteration*  so most of the time you'd just pay that extra cost for nothing  because you have to finally compare key value anyway. Actually  in one of the first versions I had a bug  where capacity of the hashtable was incorrectly 4 times bigger than should be  and the test coverage showed that this condition in line 93 was never false during the whole test suite (which led me to discover that bug with sizing  and added another test for that). BTW: There is one bigger thing I found by profiling that influences performance - there are some wasteful calls to `find` in `siftDown` and `siftUp`  because the same key is being moved ("bubble" like) over and over again  instead of moving it only in the last step when its final position is known.

AUTHOR: jeromekelleher
BODY: Yeah  this is cleaner all right. What I'm really keen to do though is abstract away all of this paging logic away from the individual methods. Paging should be implemented exactly once  and I think a nice way to do it is to make  accessor methods (`getVariants`  `getVariantSets`  etc) that are generators over all the objects specified in the request. There are some details about how we deal with pageTokens  but I'm sure we can figure this out. I outlined this idea in the discussion for #10 earlier.I guess the larger point here is that I don't see much of this code as 'final'; a lot of it needs to be aggressively refactored as we generalise to support the rest of the protocol. As we refactor it we should definitely examine the style and make sure that it's as easy as possible to understand.

AUTHOR: vadimcn
BODY: Yes  they'd all end up on the PATH and then the first one wins.   In order to support side-by-side installation of multiple Rust versions  we should probably consider leaving PATH alone (or at least making this feature not selected by default)  and providing shortcuts in the Start menu that open console window with PATH set for the appropriate Rust version.Another interesting question is whether 32-bit and 64-bit versions should be considered the same product.   Right now they are  and installing  say  a 64-bit version uninstalls the 32-bit one (and vice-versa)  which is kinda bad.On the other hand  if we bundled both 32- and 64-bit versions of Rust libraries  there'd be no reason to want to install both  because one could just use the `--target` switch to select bitness of the generated executables.

AUTHOR: Dunbaratu
BODY: While I like the idea of eventually making it so that we are using a sort of ListValue that enforces that only kOS objects are ever seen by a kerboscript  I don't really think it can work as a halfway solution like this  and trying to do it will just mean more work later if we have to rip it out and re-do it  thus my comment.  I think the path to doing what you're trying for here would be this:Step 1: Make a base class (or an interface - I'm thinking interface so we can multiply inherit)  let's call it KOSUserObject  from which ALL objects kerboscript sees derives from.  When a user does SET X TO 1. They don't get a native Integer  they get a KOSNumber which is a subclass of KOSUserObject.  When a user does SET S TO "HELLO" they don't get a native string  they get a KOSString  which is a subclass of KOSUserObject  and so on.Step 2: Enforce this in the stack and in the dictionary - making it only accept a limited set of objects - all of type KOSObject.  A KOSObject is either a KOSUserObject or a KOSMachineObject - UserObjects being the stuff script see and MachineObjects being stuff the VM needs to exist on the stack  like delegates and the like.Step 3: make it so that the LIST() that scripts use is only allowed to contain objects of type KOSUserObject.

AUTHOR: freakboy3742
BODY: For me  something tied to `auto_created` makes more sense - what we're trying to capture here is whether the field is a canonical representation  or the "other" side that needs to exist for data access purposes  but doesn't require explicit action (because the action will happen on the canonical side). If we were to tie this to `one_to_one`/`one_to_many`  then we're assuming that a `one_to_one`/`one_to_many` field will always be the canonical representation requiring action. GenericRelations show how this isn't necessarily the case. A theoretical "OneToManyField" (i.e.  a "reverse" definition of a ForeignKey) would be another interesting case - that's a field where the "concrete" column is on the reverse  auto-created object.

AUTHOR: samertm
BODY: This changeset doesn't handle deleted files. If a file is deleted froma source unit  the source unit will only be recomputed if another filethat belongs to the source unit is changed. It makes sense to fix thiseventually  but I didn't think it was a blocking issue.It will handle renamed or moved files if they're added to git's index.The trade-off here is whether to rely on the file system's state orthe scm's state when making the decision of whether we should cache abuild file. I decided to go with the scm because there's an actionassociated with changed and unchanged source units: changed sourceunits need to be rebuilt  and unchanged source units need to becopied. Relying on a makefile makes sense when the choice is betweenaction and inaction. Additionally  we want srclib to know whatsource units have changed when we start rebuilding unchanged sourceunits that depend on units that have changed  and to check if a cachedbuild file exists before copying it. I think that relying on the scmfor this information is more clear.If we use globs to see if a makefile has changed  then we're relyingon every toolchain to pass us the correct globs (which isn't a bigdeal  but I think that doing less work with each individual toolchainis better reliability's sake)  and we're using the state of thefilesystem to tell us whether a file changed  instead of the scm. Idon't think that's a big deal for builds on our site  because thebehavior will be the same using either method  but for using srclibinteractively  "srclib builds every unit that changed since the lastbuilt commit" is more clear to me than "srclib builds every unit sincethe last time it ran". If a build of source unit can fail based on thestate of another source unit  then it's less reliable to rebuild basedon the file's modification time.I think getting the state of a repo from the scm makes more sense  butI'm open to the idea of using globs and mtimes instead if there's aconvincing case for it.This branch will do the right thing when given your example if the newfile is added to git's index (once I finish responding to your comments).

BODY: Have you tested this code? It's likely there are timing issue with this and that's the reason there is a wait loop (which isn't infinite btw).Without it what can happen is you can have `available() > 0` but `read() == -1` if you process too fast (you get the correct length from +IPD but `_serial` isn't available yet. BODY: We consider explicitly referencing the `subject` from an example to be a a code smell:http://blog.davidchelimsky.net/blog/2012/05/13/spec-smell-explicit-use-of-subject/In addition  you've mixed `expect(subject)` with `is_expected` (which does the exact same thing). It would be good to stick with one style. Elsewhere we've tended to use `is_expected` for its terseness (to keep the focus on the matchers) but this case is slightly weird in that the default subject is an instance of `Baz` (thus forcing you to explicitly define it).  Given that  I think I might favor using `specify { expect(Baz).to ... }`.

AUTHOR: immortius
BODY: float deltas are in seconds  not milliseconds. So the renamed parameter is incorrect.I threw performance monitoring around most methods in the renderer to determine where time was spent. Yes  updateTick() probably doesn't have much cost  but I wasn't going to assume that. Feel free to strip some out as you go. In general I guess the approach is to have the monitor around some top level method  and only drilling down if more information is needed.I put them around methods rather than in methods simply because methods can have multiple return locations - having them around the methods avoid the need for try/finally or multiple endActivity statements  and basically dodges maintenance errors that introduce new return locations.The Performance monitor is different from profiling. Profiling will tell you how much time is spent in a given method over the life of the application  but we're more interested in how time is spent each frame  and if a frame is unusually slow - why was it slow? If a method takes a second once in the running of an application then that won't really show in the profile statistics - but that would be very noticeable for a user. It also drives the in-game monitoring metrics  which means a user can report where time is spent for them without them having to set up to run from source.

In this PR  there seems to be some possible misunderstanding in how the Flyway DB integration actually initializes/upgrades a DSpace database. I don't quite understand what the problem is in the current Flyway DB integration  so it's hard to make a suggestion for how to make the changes you are attempting.

AUTHOR: jefff
BODY: There's a bit of a coffeescript gotcha here. The `@` in `@private_key` is shorthand for `this` but because it's inside of a callback  `this` won't be what you expect. The solution to this is to change the line 308 from `zlib.deflateRaw xml  (err  deflated) ->` to `zlib.deflateRaw xml  (err  deflated) =>`. The `=>` (fat arrow) at the end will cause the callback to keep the context of the caller and everything will work as expected.

BODY: I see what you mean  but I think this approach will work  because `lwork` is never overridden. So if `lwork=None` in the `rq` function call  then for both the `gerqf` and `gor_un_grq` safecall  the `lwork` parameter will be None and the optimal size would be computed first.This is also the way it works in the existing `qr` function.It appears that both [orgrq](https://software.intel.com/en-us/node/521025) and [gerqf](https://software.intel.com/en-us/node/521024) have the same requirements and optimal `lwork`  so I think sharing across all of them isn't a problem in the case that `lwork` is explicitly set to something other than `None` or `-1`.

AUTHOR: totallymike
BODY: `for-in` loops iterate over all properties of an object--even inherited or prototypical ones.  This can cause problems.  Take this for example:```javascriptArray.prototype.foo = 'bar';var arr = [1  2  3];for (var i in arr) {  console.log(arr[i]);}//=> 1//=> 2//=> 3//=> barfor (var i in arr) {  if (arr.hasOwnProperty(i)) {    console.log(arr[i]);  }}//=> 1//=> 2//=> 3```The same goes for objects:```javascriptObject.prototype.foo = 'bar';var obj = {a: 1  b: 2  c: 3}for (var i in obj) { console.log(obj[i]); }//=> 1//=> 2//=> 3//=> barfor (var i in obj) {  if (obj.hasOwnProperty(i)) {    console.log(obj[i]);  }}//=> 1//=> 2//=> 3```Now consider if we're using objects with constructors:```javascriptfunction Foo (a  b  c) {  this.a = a;  this.b = b;  this.c = c;}Foo.prototype.printAll = function () {  for (var i in this) {    console.log(this[i]);  }}var foo = new Foo(1  2  3);foo.printAll();//=> 1//=> 2//=> 3//=> [Function]//=> bar// (guess why you shouldn't monkeypatch Object ;)```

AUTHOR: weaverryan
BODY: The `HttpCache` class absolutely *does* cache responses with cookies. @ricardclau said otherwise  but in his to the code (https://github.com/symfony/symfony/blob/master/src/Symfony/Component/HttpKernel/HttpCache/HttpCache.php#L675:L690)  you'll notice that `isPrivateRequest()` is only used here: https://github.com/symfony/symfony/blob/master/src/Symfony/Component/HttpKernel/HttpCache/HttpCache.php#L508. In other words  if the response is public  then it *will* be cached by Symfony's reverse proxy.As I understand it  that *is* different than Varnish  where you need to do some VCL stuff  because by default it will not cache any response with headers. Is that right?My point is that this should be re-worded a little bit: some reverse proxies refuse to cache responses with cookies by default (Varnish) while others will cache them  which will mean that every user after the first will get a response with the wrong CSRF token.

AUTHOR: sarken
BODY: We already load jQuery and jQuery UI on all our pages  so you'll need to remove lines 62-71. In order to ensure that the jquery.timeago.min.js script loads after jQuery  you _could_ do this:```<%= content_for :footer_js do %>  <script src="/javascripts/jquery.timeago.min.js" type="text/javascript"></script>  <script type="text/javascript">    $(document).ready(function() {      $("abbr.timeago").timeago();   });  </script><% end>```However  it's a pretty useful script that I can easily see us wanting to use elsewhere on the site  so it would be even better to add it directly to the /views/layouts/_javascripts.html.erb file: `<%= javascript_include_tag "jquery.scrollTo.min"  "jquery.livequery.min"  "rails"  "application"  "bootstrap/bootstrap-dropdown.min"  "jquery-shuffle"  "jquery.tokeninput.min"  "jquery.trap.min"  "ao3modal.min"  "jquery.cookie"  "jquery.timeago.min" %>`Then you can put `$j('.timeago').timeago();` in the topmost section of /public/javascripts/application.js: ```$j(document).ready(function() {    setupToggled();    if ($j('#work-form')) { hideFormFields(); };    hideHideMe();    showShowMe();    handlePopUps();    attachCharacterCounters();    setupAccordion();    setupDropdown();    // remove final comma from comma lists in older browsers    $j('.commas li:last-child').addClass('last');    // make Share buttons on works and own bookmarks visible    $j('.actions').children('.share').removeClass('hidden');    // convert an absolute time to a relative time  e.g. 1 day ago    $j('.timeago').timeago();    prepareDeleteLinks();    thermometer();});```(You don't need to use `abbr.timeago` because we'll never use the class name `timeago` without intending to call this script.)

AUTHOR: blairconrad
BODY: Regrettably  no. I'd've preferred it as well. `CanCreateDummyOfType` will be called on a dummy definition when we're looking for any (not yet cached) dummy definition to use. So if other tests have already tried to make dummies  there's a chance that the framework will have already called `CanCreateDummyOfType`.Right now if I make the change  it fails  as the method has been called 5 times  not 1.Of course  as I type this  I realize that I can reset the count in the test. Two secs.```csharp[Test]public void CanCreateDummyOfType_should_not_be_called_again_after_definition_for_a_dummy_type_is_found(){    // Clear the count  since CanCreateDummyOfType may have been called for other types    // in other tests.    DummyTestsDummyDefinition.TimesCanCreateDummyOfTypeWasCalled = 0;    A.Dummy<Dummy>();    DummyTestsDummyDefinition.TimesCanCreateDummyOfTypeWasCalled.Should()        .Be(1  "we need to call CanCreateDummyForType to create the Dummy");    A.Dummy<Dummy>();    DummyTestsDummyDefinition.TimesCanCreateDummyOfTypeWasCalled.Should()        .Be(1  "the definition should've been cached  so there's no need to call CanCreateDummyForType");}```The first  `Should` is practically a precondition test  which I'm not always so keen on. Say the word and I'll strike it.

AUTHOR: Haacked
BODY: So I was curious why this wasn't a problem with the `ReadOnlyCollection<T>` and `ReadOnlyList<T>`. It turns out that `List<T>` implements `IReadOnlyList<T>` and `IReadOnlyCollection<T>`.So if we change the dictionary code to create a regular `Dictionary<K V>` and return that  it _should_ just work.The one thing I don't like about that is a caller can mutate the "readonly" collections and dictionary by casting it to the concrete type.So there's several options:1. Do nothing. This is good enough. After all  it doesn't regress any existing situations.2. Change the code to return a `Dictionary<K V>` which fulfills the `IReadOnlyDictionary<K V>` contract. What this means is we don't add support for deserializing a `ReadOnlyDictionary<K  V>`.3. Add a new `ReadOnlyCollectionConstructorCache` that supports all the readonly collections. This would allow us to add support for the concrete readonly collections.4. Change `ConstructorCache` to understand readonly collections.@prabirshrestha which of these options do you most prefer. I'm leaning away from 4  but 1 - 3 seem acceptable to me :smile: and I'm happy to do the work.

AUTHOR: freakboy3742
BODY: I disagree - To my mind  ForeignKeys are One-to-many: they're "one" on the side that defines them  and "many" on the other side. This is backed up by the fact that the "other" side of a ForeignKey is a ManyToOneRel. It's worth noting that this same confusion exists in various [Entity-Relationship diagram notations](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entity–relationship_model#Cardinalities) - the side on which you put the visual "many" varies (c.f. Martin/Crow foot and IDEF1X notation). So  to some extent  this is a bikeshed; my preference would be to stick with the notation we've been using historically.

AUTHOR: peterbe
BODY: I'm almost embarrassed by this but you need to do only `select2.css` and `select2-bootstrap.css` together in one block of `compress css`/`endcompress`.The reason is that if you look for places where `select2-bootstrap.css` is used  throughout the project  you'll see that there are many places where it uses these two together. When the `compress css` thing works  it turns that into one file with a unique name. E.g. a3ed10efaa2.css and that gets reused throughout the management pages. So  if you make a combination of those two plus one more it gets a different unique name and the browser won't know it's already downloaded parts of it so you get excess downloaded. The solution would be to do this:```html{% compress css %}<link href="{{ static('select2/select2.css') }}" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css"><link href="{{ static('select2/select2-bootstrap.css') }}" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">{% endcompress %}{% compress css %}<link href="{{ static('manage/css/survey.css') }}" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">{% endcompress %}```

AUTHOR: vickychijwani
BODY: This isn't related to the jQuery update  right? Don't change this now  but you could've committed this separately. Each commit should follow the Unix philosophy: do one thing  and do it well. This is so that it's easy to revert problematic commits without affecting other changes (e.g.  you might end up reverting some unrelated bug fixes  unintentionally)  and so it's easy to understand the project history. Check out these [guidelines for git commits][1]. `git add -p` is especially powerful for cases like the current one (basically it lets you stage _parts_ of your diff rather than the entire file at once).Also  once you're comfortable with git's basics  you could start using [`git rebase -i`][2] to amend  squash  or re-order commits  making sure they are well-formed before you publish them. That way you can make commits quickly when you're in the thick of coding without worrying too much and clean up later.Don't feel pressured to implement all this in your workflow immediately  but try to keep moving towards that end goal. It'll help a lot in the long run  I think.PS: I hope you don't mind me lecturing so much :stuck_out_tongue_winking_eye:[1]: http://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Distributed-Git-Contributing-to-a-Project[2]: https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/rewriting-history/git-rebase-i

BODY: Yes. BODY: Right  I'm not arguing whether it's useful to have such an accessor (I agree on that point). I'm arguing against the user paying the cost of fetching that object or datatype up-front  by default. Consider that they might want to display a list of search results directly out of the index  using stored fields; forcing their search result to fetch each object in the list adds substantial latency. Also  since the `ResultCollection#each` method calls `[]` (which returns the RObject)  rather than yielding each document  they can't opt-out as easily.

AUTHOR: eddyb
BODY: My ordering would allow strictly more programs to compile  it doesn't affect side effects  and it's quite deterministic.Evaluating the receiver and the auto-borrow on it *are not* coupled. The evaluation includes side effects and reodering it would be disastrous  while an *lvalue* auto-borrow (and even an explicit borrow) can be placed anywhere between the evaluation of the lvalue and when it is actually needed (i.e. the argument is required for the call).Moving the borrows later effectively shrinks the duration of the borrow  potentially removing overlaps with other borrows  but never adding new overlaps.On top of that  we can also reorder *just* the evaluation of the autoderef on the receiver  not the entire receiver  spec'ing it as being evaluated as part of the second pass over the arguments. Even if restricting `Deref` impls to have no side-effects (using an `unsafe trait`) to get this behavior is doable  I don't think it's necessary.

AUTHOR: MiguelCastillo
BODY: Here we can wrap this with a `describe` with text that describes what's happening.  One thing that's even harder than naming variables is coming up with text for unit tests.  I would call this something like `describe("and deep3 is loaded"  function() {});`Then each `expect` below is wrapped in a single `it` describing what the test is doing.  For example  you can have something like:``` javascriptit("deep3 is an object"  function() {  expect(result).to.be.an("object");});it("deep3 has only one property"  function() {  expect(Object.keys(result).length).to.equal(1);});it("deep2 is an object"  function() {  expect(result.deep2).to.be.an("object");});```The idea is to have readable output that gives you an idea of what is being tested.One thing I just noticed is that the data in `deep3.js` is a bit wrong.``` javascriptBitloader.define(["js/deep2"]  function(deep2) {  return {    "deep3": deep2  };});```should really be ``` javascriptBitloader.define(["js/deep2"]  function(deep2) {  return {    "deep2": deep2  };});```Those `deep` module can probably use a little adjustment to make more readable tests.

AUTHOR: mbabker
BODY: You change the known behavior of the API endpoint with that.  At present  not supplying a second param applies the PHP `DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR` constant for the path separator which means when used in a Windows environment  paths are returned with a `\` separator.  The change forces it to return Unix style `/` separators by default.  Yes  this is an edge case  but the fact is that it changes the default behavior of the endpoint and can cause a break in scripts using `JPath::clean()`.  Therefore  by the policy  because this is not a private method it must retain B/C until a major version increment.  In truth  we did a lot of things against that policy which is why we considered 3.3.0 to not follow the strategy published in 2014 but rather the previous version of the development strategy.

AUTHOR: mbabker
BODY: In theory  I agree totally.  However  there's a reason the policy was written the way it is (something I had a hand in).  There isn't lenience for "well  it probably won't break anything" situations like this; it essentially comes down to "Is this change breaking B/C?  If yes  do this..." style logic.  It hurts our code base a little during the growth of a major release series  but the intent is to provide a stable API which doesn't introduce breaking changes in the middle of it.Perfect example  if you see the first working version of the install adapter code I worked on with a couple others a couple years ago and compare it to what is being proposed now  you'll see a lot more B/C considerations in the PRs; the original code took no consideration for that but having that end state (working code with a desired goal) allowed me to work backwards to integrate it in a B/C manner and introduce a roadmap into v4 (within those classes at least) and what B/C breaking changes are suggested to occur.

AUTHOR: claudiob
BODY: Before this PR  returning `false` in an ActionDispatch callback did not have any side effect.After this PR  returning `false` in an ActionDispatch callback halts the chain and shows a deprecation warning.The Rails codebase uses two ActionDispatch callbacks [defined here](https://github.com/rails/rails/blob/8a1c3476a62005e3cb7cfe440da71b94fab8aa5b/actionpack/lib/action_dispatch/middleware/reloader.rb#L32L51)  namely `ActionDispatch::Reloader#to_prepare` and `#to_cleanup`.In the code above  I added `presence` to prevent the body of the `#to_prepare` callback from returning `false` and  therefore  halting the callback. In fact the `execute_if_updated` method above explicitly returns `false` sometimes ([source code](https://github.com/rails/rails/blob/8a1c3476a62005e3cb7cfe440da71b94fab8aa5b/activesupport/lib/active_support/file_update_checker.rb#L82L89)):```rubydef execute_if_updated  if updated?    execute    true  else    false  endend```---Looking back at the code now  I realize that a better alternative to the `.presence` above might be to explicitly declare a custom terminator for  `ActionDispatch::Reloader#to_prepare` and `#to_cleanup`  overriding for these specific case the default terminator  so they never halt the chain  not even when `false` is returned or `:abort` is thrown. In other words  replacing [these two lines](https://github.com/rails/rails/blob/master/actionpack/lib/action_dispatch/middleware/reloader.rb#L32L33):```rubydefine_callbacks :preparedefine_callbacks :cleanup```with something like:```rubydefine_callbacks :prepare  terminator: ->(target  result) { false }define_callbacks :cleanup  terminator: ->(target  result) { false }```@rafaelfranca Would you rather go this direction?

AUTHOR: viesturz
BODY: Is there a reason you want to go with this specific evaluation order? A Google search did not produce any documentation on this.Your workaround would work for simple cases. It will break apart unpredictably at more complex cases. Such unpredictably would really frustrate the users.What about debug mode with optimizations disabled? Would it still reorder stuff? What to do if you need a mutable borrow to evaluate parameters:    obj.paint(obj.x  obj.y  obj.getCachedOrDownloadImage())Or a mutable borrow to get to the function to call:    obj.getSomethingMutablyBorrowsObj().someFunction(obj.name)  To generalize self is just another parameter. If more than one parameter needs to borrow ob after a mutable borrow is done  there is no way out.We can either define an order that would work for most cases or leave it undefined and let compiler to figure out if there is a evaluation order that complies with borrow restrictions.It's much more likely that self will need a mutable borrow of obj than the other parameters. Thus I'm for evaluating self last to allow more code to work.

AUTHOR: ashihaby
BODY: I am sure of that  you can test it too  the replayer send this message here ```def shutdownWithObjectSubscriptionAck(reason: String) = {    shutdown(reason)    objectSubscriber ! SubscriptionFailure(r  500  reason)  }```What happens here is  first the replayer will terminate and the `objectSubscriber` will receive terminate message as it watch the replayer and will enter this case which will send the first failure message to the client```case Terminated(actor) =>      subscriptionFailed(505  "Associated replayer stopped")``` In the second line you send `objectSubscriber ! SubscriptionFailure(r  500  reason)` which will enter this case ```case SubscriptionFailure(r  errorCode  reason) =>      subscriptionFailed(errorCode  "Internal Server Error")```and the client will receive the second message

AUTHOR: ShimShtein
BODY: This is a mix-and-match approach.The data-col is responsible for the start point of the widget  and the sizex is responsible for the widget width  so if you want for example a widget that is located on the third column and is 5 columns wide  you will mark it with `data-col=3 data-sizex=5`. Each of the properties is responsible for a different property of the element: data-col is about margins (offset)  data-sizex is about width  so you can't put them in the same selector like you've shown.The only thing that I am not sure about  is moving both elements to a single loop. I don't think it is a better  because it will cause a less nicer CSS in the output that is more confusing:```css[data-col=1] {margin: ...}[data-sizex=1] {width: ...}[data-col=2] {margin: ...}[data-sizex=2] {width: ...}```

AUTHOR: flying-sheep
BODY: you mean `d[exc_class]`. `e` is an exception instance.and that would create an edge case:```pythonapp = Flask(__name__)# hierarchy: Exception → OSError → ConnectionError → ConnectionAbortedError@app.errorhandler(OSError)def handle_os_error(e):    ...app.run()somewhere during runtime some connection aborts  a ConnectionAbortedError instance is raised. now  due to your caching: `d[ConnectionAbortedError] is d[OSError]`also during runtime (after that)  some new error handler is registered. (not inconceivable):```python@app.errorhandler(ConnectionError)def handle_connection_error(e):    ...```well fuck  now another ConnectionAbortedError instance being raised won’t trigger the newly registered error handler but the cached one!---we can circumvent this by instead having a separate dict holding all cached handlers  and clearing all superclasses of a newly registered exception from that cache handler dict. like so:```python# in __init__:self._error_handler_cache = {}# in _register_error_handler:for superclass in exc_class.mro():    try:        del self._error_handler_cache[superclass]    except KeyError:        pass# in _find_error_handler → find_superclass (after “if not d: return None”):handler = self._error_handler_cache.get(exc_class)if handler is not None:    return handler# in _find_error_handler → find_superclass (before returning the handler):self._error_handler_cache[exc_class] = handler```

AUTHOR: prabirshrestha
BODY: Shouldn't directly use `ReflectionUtils.GetConstructor` as it doesn't cache. `ConstructorCache` should be used. Using cache increases the 2nd and nth performance drastically.`GetConstructor` can internally call `GetConstructorByReflection` or `GetConstructorByExpression` depending on the settings. The performance impact will be seen on `GetConstructorByExpression` since it needs to compile the lambda expression. Compiling lamda expression are slow and hence is only done once when using the cache. https://github.com/facebook-csharp-sdk/simple-json/blob/f739f0b2924bcfa33204e86b8b73aa98be68abac/src/SimpleJson/SimpleJson.cs#L1861Here is the (cryptic) benchmark that shows a huge performance gain. https://gist.github.com/prabirshrestha/2433886#file-benchmark-on-net-4-client-profile-L17ctor compiled lambda00:00:00.0051271 // first run00:00:00.0000074 // second runbenchmark code can be found at https://github.com/facebook-csharp-sdk/reflection-utils/blob/e1ef1b8dca63efb0826e85bc4987f1685537a7ca/src/ReflectionUtils/ReflectionUtilsBenchmarks.cs

AUTHOR: webmozart
BODY: > a PHPCR resource is dynamicSure  you would either need to invalidate the cache when the resource changes or rebuild it periodically.> what are we caching?That depends on the repository you are adding the resource to. In the case of the FilesystemRepository  the resource is simply dumped to the filesystem and returned again as a File/DirectoryResource. The metadata will be lost  but in many cases accessing the body only will be sufficient.You could also implement another type of repository that uses `serialize()` and stores the resource metadata - for example - in a key-value store. There surely are plenty of other use cases and possible cache implementations  depending on what needs to be cached  how often the cache needs to be accessed/refreshed  how fast it needs to be etc.The point I'm trying to convey is: I want to give the users of Puli the chance to build custom repository implementations that are highly specialized to the needs of their applications. They can then take a generic repository (which may be less efficient  less effective  ...) and copy the resources to their own highly specialized one with very little effort.

AUTHOR: mlavin
BODY: Keeping them all in their own directory serves a couple of purposes. It makes it easy to exclude them from the `lint-js` command. It also makes it clear that these scripts came from a third-party and should not be modified in the repo other than to upgrade the version. Keeping them contained in a single directory also makes it easier to change this to use an existing package manager (`npm`  `bower`  `volo`  `jam`  etc) rather than downloading them via `wget`. This is a general location for third-party client source files which might include CSS/LESS/SASS frameworks where nesting this under `js` would not make sense.

AUTHOR: amitgandhinz
BODY: Yes.  Basically when a purgeAssets() operation is submitted  poppy will instruct the CDN provider to purge those assets from their edge.  It may take some time for the CDN operator to purge the asset across their entire edge network.  When a user then accesses the site  the edge will pull from origin if that content has been purged from the edge server being accessed.If that content is no longer found at origin  then the edge server will return a 404.  As that is handled by the provider  I recommend reading the provider docs  but this is generally how it works with most providers.

AUTHOR: alexbaumgertner
BODY: АВМ в легких может может диагностироваться как аномальные проявление легких на рентгенограмме грудной клетки  или как гипоксия (низкий уровень кислорода) на пульсоксиметрии или газов артериальной крови. Пузырь контраст эхокардиографии (пузырь эхо) могут быть использованы в качестве скрининга для выявления аномальных связи между артерий и вен легких. Это включает в себя введение перемешиваемой физиологического раствора в вену  а затем с помощью ультразвука на основе визуализации сердца. Как правило  легкие удалить мелкие пузырьки воздуха из кровотока  и они  следовательно  можно увидеть только в правом предсердии и правом желудочке. Если AVM присутствует  появляются пузырьки в левом предсердии и левом желудочке  как правило  3-10 сердечных цикла после правой стороны; это медленнее  чем в пороков сердца  в которых есть прямые связи между правой и левой стороны сердца.Большее количество пузырьков  скорее всего  указывают на наличие АВМ. Bubble эхо не является идеальным инструментом отбора  как он может пропустить мелкие АВМ и не определить место АВМ. Часто контрастным усилением компьютерной томографии (КТ ангиография) используется для идентификации поражений легких; этот метод имеет чувствительность более 90%. [1] [2] Это может быть можно опустить контрастности управления на современных компьютерных томографов. [5] Эхокардиография также используется  если есть подозрение на легочной гипертензии или высокой выходной сердечной недостаточности из-за больших поражений печени  иногда с последующим катетеризации сердца для измерения давления внутри различных камер сердца.

BODY: Whenever a callback returns `false`  the user gets a deprecation warning.In the rest of the code  I have changed all internal uses of `return false` to `throw(:abort)`  so users will not get deprecation warnings for internal code.However  in this specific case  there is no need to do that because the value returned by this method (whether `nil` or `false`) is not used anywhere. The method above is [invoked here](https://github.com/rails/rails/blob/8b07f18599854475a69c1447642dd3d80bea8df9/activemodel/lib/active_model/validations.rb#L394) inside `_run_validate_callbacks`:```ruby    def run_validations! #:nodoc:      _run_validate_callbacks      errors.empty?    end```The only important thing is whether `errors` is empty or not.Since it's not meaningful whether the callback returns `false` or `not`  I added the `|| nil`  so the user will not get a useless deprecation warning. ---The following is to show you how you would get deprecation warning when running tests if you didn't add the `|| nil`:```bashDEPRECATION WARNING: Returning `false` in a callback will not implicitly halt a callback chain in the next release of Rails. AUTHOR: yuriks
BODY: I was going to say no  since I'm doing intrusive ref-counting  but now I'm trying to think if there's anything it gets us that `std::shared_ptr` and `std::shared_from_this` don't.One advantage of `boost::intrusive_ptr` is that it is the same size as a raw pointer (while `std::shared_ptr` is the size of 2 for each pointer and +2 for `std::enable_shared_from_this`.) and that it's faster due to not using atomic counting ops. (Which we don't need right now.)On the other hand  `std::shared_ptr` enables the use of `std::weak_ptr` which might simplify the implementation of some things (mostly scheduler/lock related) as they're further de-Handled. I don't think it'll be a big help  however. (Might in-fact be more complicated  code-wise.)So it's mostly memory-related concerns from me plus the fact that the `boost::intrusive_ptr` implementation is relatively tiny. (I only had to add 500 lines to our boost repo for it.)

AUTHOR: ycombinator
BODY: My understanding is that requesting assets via their CDN URLs is done out-of-band from the API. One of the pieces of information this API will return is the CDN domain name when you perform a `$cdnService->getService({serviceId})` operation. After that point  the user can simply suffix the relative path of their asset to this domain name.When all assets are purged via the `$service->purgeAssets()` operation  if the user were to request that asset via the asset URL  the service would not find the asset in its caches (located on edge nodes) and try to request it from the origin server at that point. This is my understanding but perhaps @amitgandhinz can confirm.

AUTHOR: bfontaine
BODY: `(…)` is a *capturing group*  which you can later reference using `$1` (the first matching one)  `$2` (the second)  etc. `(?:…)` is a *non-capturing group*  meaning we don’t care about having it in the resulting match. See [this explanation on SO](http://stackoverflow.com/a/3513858/735926).```irb>> $1 if "bar foo qux" =~ /foo/nil>> $1 if "bar foo qux" =~ /(foo)/"foo">> $1 if "bar foo qux" =~ /(?:foo)/nil```This is used when you want to group stuff together but don’t want to capture it.

I was wondering if we should provide an option to mark the files document as being deleted before issuing any actual delete operation  delete the chunks first and then finally delete the files document. AUTHOR: MichaelDiBernardo
BODY: I have a suggestion for this section. Instead of discussing `what-if` and lazy argument evaluation together  I suggest:a) Identifying that users can't really call `transact-on-db` directly  because if they provide e.g. a literal list of them in a REPL  the list will be evaluated b) We thus provide a higher-level `transact` call  which is actually a macro. The reason why this helps is because we basically get a form of lazy evaluation out of it. Instead of parameterizing `_transact` at this stage  I would explicitly call `*swap*` from within `_transact` to support only this use case.c) Go through your macro expansion examples for `_transact` to describe how this works in practice.d) Split out the `what-if` implementation into a short subsection. You're lucky of course that both are foreign keys  so they would be set to None - but that's not really clean.Eventually  this will always be bypassed except for the first PUT. Even if you try to DELETE  it will return a "created". Somehow this is a bit dodgy - maybe don't try tricks?

AUTHOR: jefrailey
BODY: `dict[key] = value` binds the key to the value inside the dictionary even if that key was previously bound. As such  donors added to `Donators` will have their donation history replaced with the newest donation. The goal of the assignment is to create a program that will track all previous donations. New donations for existing donors should be appended to their existing list. BODY: `Donators` is a dictionary  which means values can be easily extracted from it via the associated key. It's relatively  incredibly inefficient to iterate over the keys in the dictionary to find the desired value.

AUTHOR: jefrailey
BODY: This `else` clause belongs to the `for` loop  which means it will execute if and only if the loop ["terminates through exhaustion"](https://docs.python.org/2/tutorial/controlflow.html#break-and-continue-statements-and-else-clauses-on-loops). Since `send_thankyou()` adds the donor's name to `Donators`  `i == DonorName` must evaluate to `True` at some iteration in the loop. This means line 30's `return` statement will occur before the loop exhausts the list  so the `else` clause will never be reached. Based on the body of the `else`  `print u"Enter an integer:"`  I suspect this is not operating as you intended.

AUTHOR: smarterclayton
BODY: I was saying account names is redundant with user names - teams and groups and roles are functionally identical  so need to be thought of as distinct but similar.  Teams or something like them stays.The goal of roles is to apply a consistent set of policy rules similar to how team abstracts a group of people.  You have the pieces of that  but I'm not sure that the distinct binding resources are necessary.Use case: I want to apply the same set of policy and roles to large numbers of project. When a new project is created it automatically gets a policy and roles. As an admin  I can globally change the policy of a single role and have it applied to all projects using that policy.Use case: I want to customize the policy of a project  and have that policy inherit the bulk of its logic from the original policy.  Is it acceptable for the policy to be copied (so now there are two policies)?  If an admin customizes that policy  it's likely they want to reuse that customized policy.Open questions:1. How do admins ensure the right policy is assigned on project creation?  Does a deployer of OpenShift have to wrap project creation?2. When an admin customizes a policy to set roles  what are the odds they want to allow project admins to modify the policy?> On Jan 2  2015  at 2:14 PM  David Eads <notifications@github.com> wrote:> > In docs/proposals/policy.md:> > > +	AttributeRestrictions interface{}> > +	// ResourceKinds is a list of kinds this rule applies to> > +	ResourceKinds []string> > +}> > +> > +// PolicyRuleBinding builds on top of a PolicyRule.  It adds who information (usernames  teamnames  accountnames) > > +// and namespace information (ObjectMeta).  PolicyRuleBindings only apply to the namespace they are contained in.  > > +// That means the full set of PolicyRuleBindings for a namespaced request are contained inside of the requested > > +// namespace or in the global namespace> > +type PolicyRuleBinding struct {> > +	kapi.TypeMeta> > +	kapi.ObjectMeta> > +> > +	UserNames    []string> > +	TeamNames    []string> > +	AccountNames []string> user names should be the only option.> > Account names I wasn't sure of  but teams seem like a good idea. It seems reasonable that someone would want to be able to easily describe a rule that says  "George can modify team memberships  but cannot modify the rules that govern what members of that team can do". The former is closer to the semantic reasoning  while the latter feels like ~~demorganized~~ **compiled** output.  The exclamation point out front just converts the "invariant" into an "if"  and the inside of the "if" is the failure condition. AUTHOR: Narann
BODY: I agree  there is a lot of SSE in many emulators. It's a shame as often  emulators whose code will remains for years have bad portability. It's also a reason why I tent to prefer shortness and brevity over _compiler compliant_ writing: Emulator code should focus on readability over performance as it make life of potential future contributors easier.I'm not a compiler expert but if we convert this:```cfor (j = 0; j < 4; j++)    summand[0][j] = leftrow[0] * row[0][j];for (j = 0; j < 4; j++)    summand[1][j] = leftrow[1] * row[1][j];for (j = 0; j < 4; j++)    summand[2][j] = leftrow[2] * row[2][j];for (j = 0; j < 4; j++)    summand[3][j] = leftrow[3] * row[3][j];```To this:```cfor (j = 0; j < 4; j++) {    summand[0][j] = leftrow[0] * row[0][j];    summand[1][j] = leftrow[1] * row[1][j];    summand[2][j] = leftrow[2] * row[2][j];    summand[3][j] = leftrow[3] * row[3][j];}```Are we sure the compiler will not detect vectorizable code and provide the same result than the first case?I'm just curious.

AUTHOR: GruffyPuffy
BODY: On my logic analyzer  I get "frames" with data looking like this:0xA1 0x1E 0x06 0xA1 0x07 0xD6 0x08 0x09 0x08 0x00 0x01 0xB7 0x01 0xB7 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x0E 0x48 0x4C 0xBA 0xC8 0xE4 0xFF This is then repeated with (if I remember correctly) 10ms delays. I did look at the message and tried to see if I could figure something out. At first I thought that it was a MODE B  but with more channels  but when I applied this  the CRC calculation failed. That is when I tested the previous (i.e. MODE B) method on the "inner" message instead. The CRC calculation matches and the result can be converted to channel data in the same way as for standard MODE B. So  for this implementation I simply "discard" the outer part of the message (but it does sync on the first 0xA1 byte. It seems to work very good  but I am not very happy with not using all of the bytes received. Note also that the baud rate is not the same as for the standard XBUS receiver.Maybe you can see any pattern in the data not used? I do not think it is an empty frame as it "surrounds" the MODE B frame I am using. However all ideas on interpreting this are welcome!

AUTHOR: nursix
BODY: For your understanding what causes the memory leak:Let your code be this:    class Example(object):        def __del__(self):            print "deleted"    example = Example()Now  when you run this in regular Python (like: python test.py)  it will print "deleted".But when you run it as web2py script (i.e. inside restricted)  you will not see any output - the instance "example" is never destructed.The reason is quite simple: the destructor method holds a reference to the exec environment  the exec environment holds a reference to the "example" instance  and the "example" instance holds a reference to the destructor method. So you have a perfect circular reference which prevents any of the three objects from being destructed because the interpreter doesn't know in which order.To break the cycle  you can add:    class Example(object):        def __del__(self):            print "deleted"    example = Example()    example = NoneThe last statement removes the reference to the "example" instance from the exec environment - thereby breaking the cycle. If you now run this through web2py  it will print "deleted".When you import a module  the Python interpreter will do this setting to None automatically - which is why this does not happen for imported modules.However  knowing this  you can avoid the problem - and hence very well put the class inside config.py since you do not have a destructor  or even if you had one  you would know how to break the cycle.

AUTHOR: peterbe
BODY: `{% block manage_content %}` instead of `{%block manage_content %}`.I know it sounds like an unimportant detail. And it is. And it's not. Quality is important because it makes projects easier to maintain. Have you heard of the [Broken Window Theory](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broken_windows_theory)Basically  if an abandoned building has broken windows  people think that it's so abandoned that anybody can spray graffiti or demolish it or do whatever they like. Just because it has broken windows. But if the windows are all fixed people leave it alone and don't make it worse. The same goes with code. If the code is neat  structured and consistent people who come and work on it will continue to uphold that tradition and will continue to follow that line. If the code is sloppy and different in different places it sets your mind that it's not important what you write so the quality slowly drops. And consistency is important because it makes it easier to read the code because you're mind doesn't get hung up on odd differences. Sorry for the long essay. I hope it helps. I hope the airmozilla code is going to last for a long time and continue to be maintained for many years.

AUTHOR: akalicki
BODY: I think you're right - when I first wrote this I was operating under a multiple-inheritance assumption but I've noticed that traits really are more useful for adding smaller bits of related functionality (e.g. PSR logging or file logging). Vimeo single-inherits from a data store object in order to read experiment info from the database  so it eased our integration there to treat everything as a trait instead of a class (essentially allowing multiple inheritance from the DB object and the planout experiment classes as well). But this increasingly seems to me like a special case and probably not one we should build the open source version around.After a bit more thought I'm thinking of consolidating into the following structure (to better mirror the Python version and use traits a bit more systematically):```Experiments/  |-- Logging/    |-- PSRLoggerTrait    |-- FileLoggerTrait (uses PSRLoggerTrait + logger to log to file)  |-- AbstractExperiment (mirror of the Experiment class in Python)  |-- DefaultExperiment (unchanged)  |-- SimpleExperiment (uses FileLoggerTrait)Namespaces/  |-- AbstractNamespace (provides higher level methods + implements addExperiment etc. in terms of these methods)  |-- SimpleNamespace (implements higher level methods using dictionaries)```As you can see I yet to do anything with the interpreter but ideally that would be a nice next step. I'm also interested to hear what @tsujeeth and @GregBowyer think!

AUTHOR: maxwellhadley
BODY: The issue I hit here was that when the device didn't exist  node-rfxcom threw an exception which wasn't being caught by my node-RED node code (the node-rfxcom client). This caused node-RED to exit ungracefully with an error. Testing for the existence of the device before trying to open it guards against starting node-RED when I've forgotten to plug in the RFXtrx433 resulting in a crash. Hence I needed a device path in the test code which is always guaranteed to exist.More recently I have been working on gracefully handling plugging in and unplugging the RFXtrx433. This caused me to delve deeper into the problem  and I think I have a better solution now. The uncaught exceptions were being thrown because the default behaviour for Serialport is 'open immediately'  however this is done from a process.nextTick() callback so any exception thrown by the open() is on a different call stack and cannot be caught. I'm now manually opening the Serialport only after the event handlers have been installed  so a failing open() emits an error event.It turns out there is a race condition which occasionally causes the open() to fail even if the device does exist at the time of the test (probably contact bounce when inserting the USB plug) so I have to handle failing open() calls anyway. I will try removing the exit test & see if I still have all the error cases covered. If so  we can happily remove the icky-ness!

BODY: > Why are policies separate from the project they are part of?Access control.  It is easy to describe and conceptualize resource kind and namespace based policy rules.  By having PolicyRuleBindings  Roles  and RoleBindings as different resource kinds  it becomes easy to control who has rights to change individual aspects of policy.It seems reasonable that someone would want to allow a group of users to modify the project description  but want a much smaller group of users to modify the policy rules restricting that project.  Keeping the resources separate makes it easy to express that scenario.

AUTHOR: fgalan
BODY: I think this should be solved in a different way. Note that  by definition  any document in the enties collection has an attributes array  thus the try/catch should not be needed if we capture the error in a early place.In particular  looking to the logs after executing the .test included in this PR I have found this:```time=2015-01-02T19:31:16.884CET | lvl=DEBUG | trans=1420223475-825-00000000001 | function=entitiesQuery | comp=Orion | msg=MongoGlobal.cpp[1108]: retrieved document: '{ $err: "Exterior shell of polygon is invalid: { type: "Polygon"  coordinates: [ [ [ -70.652788  -33.603458 ]  [ -70.64603200000001  -33.604231 ]  [ -70.646781..."  code: 16693 }'```Thus probably a better strategy is to check if the "$err" field exists in the `r` document just after `LM_T(LmtMongo  ("retrieved document ...`) and  in that case  return the proper error response to the user (I'd suggest a 500 Internal Error  using the text in "$err" to fill the details field). I think that is better than a "No context element found" (as in the current version in the code) which may be hidding structural problems in geoquery done at DB.That way we would avoid Orion to crash. However  we can do even better detecting those "Exterior shell of polygon is invalid" situation before interacting with DB  fixing them if possibe or reporting the user with a 400 Bad Input error about the problem if the situation is not easy to fix. Looking to http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21870088/exterior-shell-of-polygon-is-invalid  it seems they happen when the polygon have duplicated coordinates (this seems to be easy to detect) or is an "intersection polygon" (I'm not sure if al algorithm to reorder coordinates is easy to implement). Maybe the 500 Internat Error solution is enough for this PR. If detecting and fixing "Exterior shell of polygon is invalid" situations is difficult  we can defer it to a tech debt issue (nicetohave?).

AUTHOR: smarterclayton
BODY: When are admins found to define policies across multiple namespaces?  I don't see that as very common - it's more likely an admin wants to assign the same policy to multiple namespaces  and either modifies the shared policy  or clones it and mutates their new copy.  The objective of flexible policy is to give more control over permissions - not to mutate policy in bulk.  We do not need to have a generic policy engine - instead we need to design the policy options we need to support.  I don't think its a use case to modify a single policy and add or remove namespaces it controls  because the project is ultimately the resource that policy derives from.  The policy rules need to be set up so that admins can control policy mutation within a project  and control creation of a new project and the modification of what policies are applied to the project.

AUTHOR: cxd4
BODY: A fair question.  I will check it now  but I anticipate the answer is that it will give the same result.And yes  _"readability over performance"_ is a good  slow but steady way to ultimately achieve better performance.  I agree about prioritizing that over performance or premature optimization. :) That  and future developers understand the key to each algorithm like you said.  Forcing non-portable code or prematurely optimizing for a limited span of targets (e.g. always use SSE intrinsics) generally worked better in the long run for closed-source projects or those that don't fully appreciate some benefits of open-source.So if we convert those 4 separate loops I wrote into one single loop as you implied  GCC yields:  the exact same output for both methods!  So yes  your method of changing my loop produces the exact same output within almost certainly any compiler intelligent enough to vectorize them in the first place.  To be more specific  the output it produces is:`movss   xmm0  DWORD PTR leftrow``shufps  xmm0  xmm0  0``mulps   xmm0  XMMWORD PTR row``movaps  XMMWORD PTR summand  xmm0``movss   xmm0  DWORD PTR leftrow+4``shufps  xmm0  xmm0  0``mulps   xmm0  XMMWORD PTR row+16``movaps  XMMWORD PTR summand+16  xmm0``movss   xmm0  DWORD PTR leftrow+8``shufps  xmm0  xmm0  0``mulps   xmm0  XMMWORD PTR row+32``movaps  XMMWORD PTR summand+32  xmm0``movss   xmm0  DWORD PTR leftrow+12``shufps  xmm0  xmm0  0``mulps   xmm0  XMMWORD PTR row+48``movaps  XMMWORD PTR summand+48  xmm0``ret`As to whether I'd prefer my method of writing the loops or your method of unifying them in a single loop  they both look good to me.  Yours is probably better for organizing the same "type" of operation going on within its own body of its own loop; mine mostly just focuses on representing each SIMD instruction in C loop form for each individual one  with only a theoretically better chance at enforcing the vectorization individually.  It's a hard syntactical habit of mine for me to break.But there is also an option C) here as well if you are interested:  You could also do--`int j  k;``for (k = 0; k < 4; k++)``    for (j = 0; j < 4; j++)``        summand[k][j] = leftrow[k] * row[k][j];`

AUTHOR: ktind
BODY: Protobuf handles changes to the model rather well. This is why most of the fields are marked as optional in the proposed definition. From the [protobuf docs](https://developers.google.com/protocol-buffers/docs/overview)>You can add new fields to your message formats without breaking backwards-compatibility; old binaries simply ignore the new field when parsing. So if you have a communications protocol that uses protocol buffers as its data format  you can extend your protocol without having to worry about breaking existing code.

AUTHOR: cxd4
BODY: I like it  too.  Unfortunately  I just checked  and it did not provide the same assembly language results.It added dynamic shuffle instruction code due to the new `k` variable  where shuffling one element across all four single-precision floating-point elements of the 128-bit xmm was no longer as fixated when using a loop variable instead of a literal 0  1  2  3 for array index.This is unfortunate I think  since we seem to agree that this option C) at the bottom of my reply is more readable.  Maybe it will go away in a future version of the GCC compiler  and you can use it without any performance loss whatsoever.  I sometimes observe that the current version of GCC is not good at auto-vectorizing but that the upcoming release of GCC will have such volatility fixed; you can try that if you want.  I am currently compiling on 32-bit Linux with GCC 4.8.2; you might have a better version for this particular limit.Here is the exact   full C code I am using to debug this btw:```float summand[4][4]  leftrow[4]  row[4][4];int main(void){    register unsigned int j  k;    for (k = 0; k < 4; k++)        for (j = 0; j < 4; j++)            summand[k][j] = leftrow[k] * row[k][j];    return 0;}```Compiled with:`gcc -S -O3 -msse2 -o /home/no/m64/main.s /home/no/m64/main.c`Omit the `-msse2` flag if compiling in GCC for 64-bit x86 code.Check `main.s` for the assembly language results of the code.It was the same with the first two methods I gave  but the third method for all its readability and flexibility seems less rigid to the compiler's ability to guarantee single-move shuffling in the SHUFPS op-code.

AUTHOR: NahimNasser
BODY: i'm always weary of using things like kwargs['group_id']. The scenario that has stung me in the past is when group_id is not in kwargs. This could be guaranteed if you're using a rigid well defined serializer --- but if you're not  then i would make sure to handle that scenario so a catastrophic 500 error isn't thrown.You could handle this through a try/catch or by using kwargs.get('group_id'  None) which returns None if group_id isn't there. Then you can handle the scenario with an if statement.Both approaches are valid.

AUTHOR: etiennesegonzac
BODY: I don't think we have a strong enough justification to expose `Statusbar.getIcon` through `Service`.We're only using the queuing support of `service.js`  but apart from that the `Statusbar` doesn't really need to expose `getIcon` to the world.I don't see any elegant solution to solve the DOM sharing between the statusbar and icons  but I'd like to settle on something that doesn't "pollute" `Service`.My suggestion is to dispatch a `statusbarrendered` event at the end of `StatusBar#renderIcons` and to wait for this event instead of doing the `Service.request('Statusbar:getIcon')`.We could even make a small private (to the `base_icon.js` IIFE) helper in order to end up with something like:```    waitForElement().then(function(element  early) {      this.element = element;      this.element.classList.toggle('active'  early);      this.onrender && this.onrender();      this.UPDATE_ON_START && this.update();    }.bind(this)).catch(function(error) {      console.log(error);    });````waitForElement` would maintain a `_statusbarRendered` piece of state global to `base_icons.js` and* resolve `(element  true)` if `_statusbarRendered` is `false` but `getElementById` returns something* otherwise wait for the event (and update `_statusbarRendered`) then resolve with `(element  false)`* and resolve `(element  false)` right away if `_statusbarRendered` is `true`

AUTHOR: cxd4
BODY: That's fine.  In particular  my point is  only the C code (also thought of as the "auto-vectorized" code) has universal meaning.  Anything else like inline assembly  or assembly language intrinsics  is in the eye of the beholder and not naturally readable code to everyone--because  its readability is dictated more by the target processor.For example  suppose you might prefer the intrinsic use:`ALIGNED int32_t a[4]  b[4]  c[4];int main(void) {    *(__m128i *)c = _mm_and_si128(*(__m128i *)a  *(__m128i *)b);    return 0;}`However  I find it even more readable to both the human and the compiler (for better optimizations outside the version of the SIMD instruction set architecture assumed by the usage of that intrinsic) to instead say:`int a[4]  b[4]  c[4];int main(void) {    register unsigned int i;    for (i = 0; i < 4; i++)        c[i] = a[i] & b[i];    return 0;}`Although the name of the `_mm_and_si128` intrinsic is self-explanatory as to the operation of the code  the algorithm itself is more readable and more natural when using C code (and the compiler is left to generate what should be the best choice of SIMD intrinsic for and'ing all elements).  This commit probably isn't the best example of that  however--you're welcome to disagree whether my C loops are as readable as some of the old code.  The gist of it may have been portability  but I thought it was more readable to divide each parallelized step of the overal algorithm into its own loop.  The original C loop code you had was much better than mine  thougin terms of shortness and brevity--maybe open to interpretation on the parallel steps what goes on.  So I think it's fine if certain sketchy examples of this practice come up that you like to comment about.

AUTHOR: immortius
BODY: Not the asset manager. ShaderManagerLwjgl. These are not automatically generated assets based on a naming convention! These are specific materials generated by the rendering system. They are also purely for the internal usage of the rendering system - these are the materials used by the ShaderParameter classes. Ideally we would eventually phase them out  replaced with a shader variable semantics support or something  but because that is quite a body of work not really worth messing with.There is not a one to one relationship between materials and shaders  and in general a shader does not have enough information to generate a material (since it doesn't have values for the shader's variables - this is why a material exists). A shader is included in the MaterialData class used to generate a material. So if you want a material for a given shader  you make it.

BODY: I really like the way this is all done.  The asynchronous nature of file watching is difficult to capture  but I think you nailed it.My only concern is that if the test times out for some reason  the `watchProc` won't get killed since that only happens in this listener.  I'm thinking we should move it out into an `after` [hook](http://mochajs.org/#hooks) to prevent any zombies.  Something like:```javascriptdescribe('jade --watch'  function() {  // enclose the whole suite  var watchProc;  var stdout = '';  it('watch test one'  function() {})  // first test  it('watch test two'  function() {})  // second test  after(function() {  // runs after the suite (both tests) finish    if (watchProc != null) watchProc.kill('SIGINT');  });});```

AUTHOR: apasel422
BODY: `Rev` does not have a default type of `Natural`  and it actually cannot have that be the case because `Natural` is itself parameterized by `Lhs` (crucial for type inference)  which would have to be added as a parameter to `Rev`. You would never be able to write```rustlet cmp = Rev;```anyway  because `Rev` contains a field  which is the comparator that it is reversing. We _could_ make the field of `Rev` (and the other adapters) public  like```rustpub struct Rev<C>(pub C);```and then you could write```rustlet cmp = Rev(Natural);```without importing `CompareExt`  but you would still have to import `Natural` and `Rev`  obviously. One positive effect of making those fields public (and it's unlikely that the representation would ever change for adapters that are so simple) is that the adapters could be used in constant expressions. The benefit of `CompareExt`  which would presumably be in some kind of prelude once we get those  is that you don't have to `use` the individual adapter types.

AUTHOR: stasm
BODY: I now see why it fails.  `GridManager` binds `_` [very early](https://github.com/mozilla-b2g/gaia/blob/a14de2c47999a65cff5c06d92625c3ef73e7fb8c/apps/homescreen/js/grid.js#L59)  when `navigator.mozL10n` is still `undefined` in tests.  Pre-mocking helps a bit  but it relies on the fact that `requireApp('homescreen/js/grid.js');` is asynchronous and I'd prefer to avoid such racy code if possible.Otherwise  `GridManager` is well-designed: all initialization happens explicitly in `GridManager.init` which is called in tests' `setupSuite`. Let's use that.I suggest you remove the assignment to `_` in `GridManager` and instead use `navigator.mozL10n.get` everywhere in the js/grid.js file.  This will fix the `TypeError` because you won't be trying to access `navigator.mozL10n.get` when `navigator.mozL10n` is `undefined`.  OTOH  when `GridManager.init` is called  you will have already mocked `mozL10n` in `setupSuite` and any subsequent `navigator.mozL10n.get` calls will call into `MockL10n`.Let me know what you think about this approach.

AUTHOR: kislyuk
BODY: IMO it's better to preserve the simpler semantics of passing the unmodified timeout value to requests (which then sets it on the socket) than it is to change it to ensure that we spend no more than `timeout` before returning (which is not a guarantee that the caller can fully rely on anyway  since it's not anything like a real-time system). The scenario of the first few requests returning quickly and the last one hanging (which is necessary to trigger the scenario of significantly missing the timeout deadline before returning) seems far-fetched to me. I agree there is a minor correctness issue  but the two applications of the timeout value really deal with different issues: the one passed to requests and set on the socket takes care of stalled out requests  while the one checked in the retry loop takes care of breaking out of the 503 retry-later mode.(We may also want to investigate using urllib3's retry support  which was introduced over the course of 2014. Maybe it better deals with this socket/total timeout duality?)

BODY: Hi  it does work. It's based on xcrun definitions for c/c++. It doesn't exclude win32 because  unlike xcrun  bash can be installed on win32 and it should work. It's wrapped as single command to bash to invoke two commands as single one - compilation and actual execution of the binary.It's true  that it's not perfect - in the same way c/c++/objective-c definitions are not perfect. They don't quote file paths properly so if there's a space in the real path  it'll fail. That's the problem with all of those definitions. Also they use hacky way of invoking two commands as one by wrapping everything as bash one-liner.If you agree to merge it I can send another patch with fixes for those definitions:- proper escaping of shell params  and- support for multiple command invocation (for compile-and-run languages) so we don't need to go through bash.

AUTHOR: alexbaumgertner
BODY: Все гены  как известно  так далеко  чтобы быть связаны с HHT код для белков в сигнальном пути TGF-β.Это группа белков  которые участвуют в передаче сигналов от гормонов роста трансформирующий фактор бета надсемейства (трансформирующего фактора роста бета  морфогенетического белка костной ткани и классов фактора роста дифференциации)  в частности  BMP9 / GDF2 и BMP10. Гормоны не проникают в клетку  но связываются с рецепторами на клеточной мембране; Затем они активируют другие белки  в конечном счете  влияющие на клеточное поведение в ряде способов  таких как клеточной выживаемости  пролиферации (увеличение числа) и дифференциации (становятся более специализированными). [1] Для сигналов гормона  чтобы быть адекватно трансдуцированных  сочетание белков необходимо: две каждого из двух типов серин / треонин-киназы конкретных типов мембранных рецепторов и эндоглина. При связан с гормоном  белки рецепторов типа II фосфорилируют (передачи) на фосфат типа I рецептор белки (из которых Alk-1 является одним)  которые  в свою очередь фосфорилирует комплекс СМАД белков (главным образом Smad1  SMAD5 и SMAD8). Эти связываться с SMAD4 и мигрируют в ядро клетки  где они действуют как факторы транскрипции и принимают участие в транскрипции определенных генов. В дополнение к пути SMAD  мембранные рецепторы также действовать на пути MAPK  который имеет дополнительные действия на поведение клеток. [2] Как Alk-1 и эндоглин выражены преимущественно в эндотелии  может быть  объясняет  почему ННТ вызывающих мутации в эти белки ведут преимущественно проблемы кровеносного сосуда. [2] [8] как ENG и ACVRL1 мутации приводят преимущественно недопроизводству из родственных белков  а не неправильное функционирование белков.

BODY: I believe the test is correct   I applied the rules in the following order:1. [Constants Must Appear Before Fields] (http://www.stylecop.com/docs/SA1203.html)2. [All static elements must be placed above all instance elements of the same type] (http://www.stylecop.com/docs/SA1204.html)3. [Elements Must Be Ordered By Access] (http://www.stylecop.com/docs/SA1202.html)4. Alphabetical orderWhen a member has no access keyword  such as private/public  the private value is assumed  thus ```const int x = 0``` is the same as ```private const int x = 0``` as you said.```const int x = 0;``` is the second to appear because is a private const. So it came after a public const field.Do you agree?

AUTHOR: xor-freenet
BODY: Not a release blocker just a FYI:You're using notifyAll() for signaling multiple different things:- Here for starting a job earlier- On line 197 for signaling completion.What might be indicated is using the Condition standard JRE class.You can derive multiple Condition objects from one Lock object which is precisely what you're doing here: You have the central Lock object being the implicit monitor of SynchronousDelayedBackgroundJob.this and multiple different things (= conditions) which you notifyAll() upon. Using the Condition API each call to notifyAll() would be a different Condition object while the Lock you obtain the Conditions from would stay the same (= the same SynchronizedDelayedBackground job).Notice however that IMHO the Condition API is sort of awkward which leads to complexified code: Conditions have spurious wakeups as well so Condition.await() returning does NOT mean that Condition.signal() was actually called. This means that you need an external way of detecting that it really was signalled (a boolean for example) which sort of voids its purpose. One would expect that await() returning 100% means that signal() was called. This might be possible to simplify by writing a wrapper class around Condition which maybe one of the popular Java class libraries already did.

AUTHOR: claudiob
BODY: > I'm pretty sure we are expecting prepare callbacks to stop if returning false. I didn't understand this sentence. In the current Rails code  ActionDispatch callbacks do not halt the chain when returning `false`. That setting is currently only present in [ActiveModel](https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/17227/files#diff-174733f2db65ef1bc53e3222d6ac0e61L20)  in [ActiveModel::Validations](https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/17227/files#diff-0cd7b1cc8e754e9ab96c72b45770767dL26)  and in [ActiveRecord](https://github.com/rails/rails/pull/17227/files#diff-174733f2db65ef1bc53e3222d6ac0e61L20).Since currently we **don't** expect ActionDispatch callbacks to halt upon returning `false`  and the new default terminator **will** halt upon returning `false` and display a warning (unless `config.active_support.halt_callback_chains_on_return_false` is set to `false`)  then I would add the following *custom* terminators for `#to_prepare` and `#to_cleanup`  so those callbacks will keep on **not halting** upon returning `false`:```rubydefine_callbacks :prepare  terminator: ->(_  result_lambda) { result_lambda.call if result_lambda.is_a?(Proc); false }define_callbacks :cleanup  terminator: ->(_  result_lambda) { result_lambda.call if result_lambda.is_a?(Proc); false }```Makes sense?

AUTHOR: nursix
BODY: You can actually take my word for this - as long as you avoid the above problem  it is safe to have classes like this in config.py. It isn't recommended - but for very specific reasons  which you can easily get around.If you don't trust my word  then an alternative could be to break the class up into functions and move those into config.py. It is questionable anyway whether this needs to be a class as you always only call a single function of the instance - but I understand that a class looks nicer and is perceived as easier to maintain.The ultimate solution for this sort of problems would be to import templates as modules (instead of executing them) - and move them into the module path (modules/templates). But that is truly a major framework change and would require hundreds of hours of work - not to even speak of the retraining of everyone who has ever worked on templates  so it is currently rather wishful thinking  or  as we use to say  something for 2.0 ;) We could equally well think of migrating Eden to django  or cherrypy.

AUTHOR: immortius
BODY: delta is in seconds (e.g. 0.02 seconds for a frame at 50 frames a second).delta * 1000 is in milliseconds (e.g. 0.02 * 1000 = 20 milliseconds).So tick is in milliseconds. Not sure how it is used  but I guess it is a remainder from my original sweep of changing all deltas from milliseconds to seconds (easier to work with for game logic IMO).You can use ```try (Closable c = new Closable()) {}``` blocks in Java. The problem is the PerformanceMonitor framework was created before we switched to Java 7 that introduced it  so hasn't been set up so that activities are a Closable object. I could add that though.The longer winded alternative is:```javaPerformanceMonitor.startActivity("Fun");try {  // ....} finally {  PerformanceMonitor.endActivity();}```
